
TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Organization-Level Analysis of Voluntary and Involuntary Turnover
AU  - Shaw, Jason D.
AU  - Delery, John E.
AU  - Jenkins, G. Douglas
AU  - Gupta, Nina
Y1  - 1998/10/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256939
DO  - 10.5465/256939
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 511
EP  - 525
VL  - 41
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Although there are many individual-level models of turnover, little research has examined the effects of human resource management practices on quit rates and discharge rates at the organizational level. This study used organization-level data from 227 organizations in the trucking industry to explore this issue. Results show that human resource management practices predict quit rates and discharge rates but that the determinants of each are quite different. Implications are derived and directions for future research suggested.
AB  - Although there are many individual-level models of turnover, little research has examined the effects of human resource management practices on quit rates and discharge rates at the organizational level. This study used organization-level data from 227 organizations in the trucking industry to explore this issue. Results show that human resource management practices predict quit rates and discharge rates but that the determinants of each are quite different. Implications are derived and directions for future research suggested.
